"Yes, sir. They should be on the road by now; we gave them time to pack some food from the mess hall." 05:00 A.M., Exodus teams up at the vehicle section. Lieutenant Xiao stands on a crate and begins to speak.
"We will head to the I-131 front-line base 50 miles outside Ianlos city. We will support the ongoing siege operation, then attack Ianlos city, and clear out the rebels there. We will use this as a base, and push into the mountains." Lieutenant Xiao explained. "Take your squad, and get ready to move out."
The platoon scattered and each unit boarded a tank under the leadership of their respective platoon leaders. Koln climbed onto the front tank of the convoy, sitting alongside Nimitz, Krees, and two new recruits.  Koln remembered that they had only arrived a few days earlier, but he didn't know much about them.  He sat on the edge of the tank, his legs dangling in the air, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment, and connecting them to his earpiece and throat microphone.
"Hey, Coler, is Harris still keeping Snowball?" Nimich asked after they settled in.
"Are you saying he stole that chicken?" Coulson remembered the scene from that morning when they stole the chicken from the farm. "No, I'm sure of it."
Koren watched another tank approach, and saw Harris and his men. He vaguely saw a small chick peeking out from behind Harris' backpack.
"Not wrong, he still raised that chicken," Kolen replied, just then the turret hatches of the tank creaked open and the commander appeared before them.
“All the tanks are on their way,” the commander said calmly and clearly into his radio. The armoured platoon's tanks and Stryker armoured vehicles roared to life, beginning to move forward. Captain Colren's Chiron tank eased off its brakes, moving forward and falling in line with the rest. The tanks formed a wedge-shaped column as they traversed the Ithanian plains. The winter blizzard had frozen the wetlands and forests, but the mud still lingered.
About an hour passed, a new recruit (Oren, whom Conway remembered), opened his mouth to ask, "Lieutenant, have you been on the front lines since the war broke out?"
"That's right, it started when Operation Inferno Fury began," Colen replied. "We thought we'd be done fighting in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Not just an underestimation," Nimitch added to the conversation. "Their weapons and forces exceed our expectations. They shot down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and the Erebus last month. Damn it, we should be able to see it on the road."
"Alright, I'll fight for the Federation bravely," Oren said resolutely, "I won't be intimidated by those terrorists."
"You're saying that now, but from what I've seen, most conscripts your age would have wet their pants when they heard the gunfire," Cres said.
"Never mind, let's see what happens," Colonel smiled and said. Osborn didn't say another word.
"Exodus Second-in-Command! Exodus Commander!" Radio crackled with a call from the colonel's communication equipment. "We've got a hot contact, bearing 20 degrees, 350 yards right-front!"
Kolrn climbed onto the tank, putting on optical goggles. Switching to thermal imaging mode, he saw a heat signal in the distance.
"Yes, I've seen them," Colonel said into his throat microphone.
"Are you the enemy?" another recruit Natalya asked.
"It doesn't show." Kolen said, opening the microphone. "Exodus link, do not fire unless attacked, first lure them out."
As they drew closer, the faint heat signal from the indistinct blotch became a clearer outline. One of them ran towards a place, picked something up, and then ran back to the small ridge. Next, these people lay down and entered the firing position.
"We've been ambushed!" Lieutenant Xiao shouted over the radio as orange flares shot out from the ridge. Bullets clattered against the tank's sides, and the team members leaped out, taking cover behind the tank. A rocket screamed in, slamming into the ground behind the tank column and exploding into shrapnel that hit one of the tanks. Another rocket struck the side of an APS-Cerberus armor patrol vehicle and exploded.
"Fire at target 1-2 and 1-3, bearing 25 degrees, 300 yards!" the tank platoon leader shouted over the radio. The main cannons of 1-2 and 1-3 fired, and shells whizzed towards the ridge, explosions sending mud and debris flying into the air.
“Deploy the sentry robots!” Knox shouted, his voice ringing out as he gazed through his binoculars at the ridge. The rear hatch of a “Hellhound” yawned open, and a soldier emerged, his ears plugged into a specialized headset. He bellowed orders into a square microphone, and two "sentry" robots sprang into action. Their metallic arms and legs splayed out to the sides, and they shot forward at a breakneck pace.
"Should we kill him or capture him?" Cres wondered aloud as he watched.
"It looks like they're after the living," Colen speculated, only to see the two sentry robots disappear into the ash and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed off the ridge, but quickly died down. After a while, the two sentry robots returned, dragging a person, a prisoner's boots leaving a trail in the mud and snow. Once they reached the safe area, the robots dumped the captive to the ground, and he crashed heavily into the mud and snow, groaning in pain.
He struggled to get up, Lieutenant Xiao walked over. Lieutenant Xiao turned to one of the sentries. "How many?"
"Three men are dead, sir," the sentry robot replied. "The rest of the personnel have escaped on foot."
Lieutenant Xiao nodded and turned to say to Korolenko and Kress, standing nearby: "Can you two take this person away?"
